    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "63b73193_f56ce25b",
        "filename": "src/gpu/gradients/GrTiledGradientEffect.fp",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 26,
      "author": {
        "id": 5640
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-10T13:38:35Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "So if I detect that floor and abs are used \"next to\" one another, for some interpretation of \"next to\"... what do I rewrite the code to?\n\nIf they\u0027re, say, nested calls buried in the middle of a complex expression, I can\u0027t just insert a noop in the \"middle\" to split it up, and trying to break the expression apart either changes evaluation order or introduces a ton of temporary variables (which normally I would trust an optimizer to eliminate, but I don\u0027t think OpenGL backends are generally very smart).\n\nI suppose I could rewrite either the abs or floor to be a call to a user-defined implementation, but I\u0027m afraid that would murder performance. Is there a better way to do it?\n\n(If we can\u0027t figure out how to rewrite the code automatically, reporting an error so the smart human at the keyboard can figure out how to rewrite it is at least an option)",
      "parentUuid": "ab1dd45a_49994d49",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 21,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 26,
        "endChar": 9
      },
      "revId": "02adfd89782e877b01544ed6aa1cc3566b52a188",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "79e0195d_826ed315",
        "filename": "src/gpu/gradients/GrTiledGradientEffect.fp",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 26,
      "author": {
        "id": 5085
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-10T15:38:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m not sure what \"next to means\" exactly either. Maybe you could take the output of floor and wrap it in a no-op like maybe trunc(floor(...))? TBH I\u0027m not really familiar with the nature of the bug were working around here.",
      "parentUuid": "63b73193_f56ce25b",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 21,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 26,
        "endChar": 9
      },
      "revId": "02adfd89782e877b01544ed6aa1cc3566b52a188",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "86bdb855_f8ff1ede",
        "filename": "src/gpu/gradients/GrTiledGradientEffect.fp",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 26,
      "author": {
        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-10T18:00:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The only spot the capability appears to be checked is in the old (and new) gradient code. The capability flag says: \"\"\"    \n// On some Intel GPUs there is an issue where the driver outputs bogus values in the shader\n// when floor and abs are called on the same line. Thus we must execute an Op between them to\n// make sure the compiler doesn\u0027t re-inline them even if we break the calls apart.\n\"\"\"\n\nDepending on how \"called on the same line\" is interpreted, we would have to actually break expressions into multiple statements and insert a no-op statement. If all we have to do is protect from some attempted inlining of floor+abs, then wrapping floor with a noop could work. In this instance, there are non-function expressions between the floor and abs that apparently were not enough to fix Intel\u0027s issue, which makes me think it any solution will have to be the former. That\u0027s going to be trickier, so perhaps Ethan\u0027s suggestion of erroring, and requiring someone to manually determine a valid no-op in each situation is the best bet.\n\nHere\u0027s the original CL where this was added by Greg: https://skia-review.googlesource.com/c/skia/+/76820 so maybe we can get his thoughts on an SkSL built-in solution?",
      "parentUuid": "79e0195d_826ed315",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 21,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 26,
        "endChar": 9
      },
